OL,3,CDoomed satellite due to crash to Earth
OL,4,Cafter nearly 30 years in space
OL,6,FAfter 13 years of orbital decay,
OL,7,Fmainly driven by solar activity, the
OL,8,Fsatellite will naturally re-enter
OL,9,FEarth's atmosphere.
OL,11,FThe satellite will break up into
OL,12,Fpieces during re-entry, the majority
OL,13,Fof which will burn up, the European
OL,14,FSpace Agency (ESA) said.
OL,16,FThe ESA is still monitoring its
OL,17,Flandfall, which is predicted to occur
OL,18,Fsomewhere over the east coast of
OL,19,Fcentral Africa.
OL,1,Wz5~k4~k7}hw1 ~k4~sj5j5~s1 G     G2/6
